VThe monthly cultural programme started by the Department of Culture, Andhra Pradesh, in all government music colleges and schools in the State, has given a welcome boost to many musicians and dancers. This month&#8217;s programme, arranged by G.V.R.Government College of Music and Dance, Vijayawada, at Gokaraju Laila Gangaraju Kala Vedika, a spacious auditorium situated on the college premises, was a novel and sumptuous programme. The college staff exclusively took part in the programme. M. Krishnamohan, K. Lakshminarsamma, K. Kurmanath and A. Sobha Lakshmmi excellently rendered compositions of almost all famous Vaggeyakaras, namely Thyagaraja, Muthuswamy Dikshitar, Syama Sastri, Ramadas, Purandaradas, Toomu Narasimhadas, Narayana Teertha, Jayadeva, Sadasiva Bramhendra, Dharmapuri Subbarayar, Swathi Thirunal, Meerabai, Patnam Subramanya Iyer and Mysore Vasudevachar.The compositions that figured in the grand musical event wereSadhinchene, the Pancharatna keertana of Thyagaraja,Himadrisuthe(Kalyani) of Syama Sastri,Sarasijanabha Sodariof Dikshitar in Nagagandhari, Patnam&#8217;sParidanamitchitein Bilahari, the Tarangam,Krishnam Kalaya Sakhiin Mukhari, Dhanasri tillana of Swathi Thirunal,Venkatachala Nilayamof Purandaradas and Ramadas&#8217;s famous Mangalam in Navaroj,Ramachandraya. All compositions were rendered by the group with fine co-ordination and clear diction. The individual renditions were Sadasiva Bramhendra&#8217;sPibare Ramarasam(Chakravakam) by Krishnamohan, Javali and Meera Bhajan by Lakshminarsamma, Annamayya keertana by Sobhalakshmi and Kshetrayya PadamLemaro(Saveri) by Kurmanath.  The programme received well-deserved applause from the audience. Fine instrumental support was provided by P. Nageswara Rao and V. Krishnaveni (violin), K. S. Govinda Rajan (veena), P. Indrakeeladri Sarma (flute), M. Vijayakumar (mridangam), V. Amritkumar (tabla), G. Steven Raju (ghatam) and T. Lakshmi Shankar (morsing). Another feature that gave colour to the programme was the erudite commentary in between the items by T. K. Choodamani. T. S. Ramachandra Rao inaugurated the programme and the principal of the music college, C. Munikumar, offered a vote of thanks and felicitated the artistes.
